 from behanna syl nj nec com chris behanna subject re cobra locks organization nec systems laboratory inc distribution usa lines five five in article doc webrider central sun com writes i was posting to alt locksmithing about the best methods for securing a motorcycle i got several responses referring to the cobra lock described below has anyone come across a store carrying this lock in the chicago area it is available through some dealerships who in turn have to back order it from the manufacturer directly each one is made to order at least if you get a nonstandard length standard is five i believe any other feedback from someone who has used this see below in article one r one five three four innraj shelley u washington edu basiji stein u washington edu david basiji writes incidentally the best lock i ve found for bikes is the cobra lock it s a cable which is shrouded by an articulated hardened steel sleeve the lock itself is cylindrical and the locking pawl engages the joints at the articulation points so the chain can be adjusted like handcuffs you can t get any leverage on the lock to break it open and the cylinder is well protected i wouldn t want to cut one of these without a torch and or a vice and heavy duty cutting wheel i have a six long cobralinks lock that i used to use for my harley she doesn t get out much anymore so i don t use the lock that often anymore it is made of three four articulated steel shells covering seven strands of steel cable it is probably enough to stop all the joyriders but unfortunately professionals can open it rather easily one freeze a link two break frozen link with your favorite method hammers work well three snip through the steel cables which i have on authority are frightfully thin with a set of boltcutters for the same money you can get a kryptonite cable lock which is anywhere from one two to seven eight thick steel cable looks like steel rope shielded in a flexible covering to protect your bike s finish and has a barrel type locking mechanism i don t know if it s adjustable but my source says it s more difficult to pick than most locks and the cable tends to squish flat in bolt cutter jaws rather than shear five eight model all bets are off if the thief has a die grinder with a cutoff wheel even the most durable locks tested yield to this tool in less than one minute fyi i ll be getting a krypto cable next paycheck later chris behanna dod one one four one nine eight three h d fxwg wide glide jubilee s red lady behanna syl nj nec com one nine seven five cb three six zero t baby bike disclaimer now why would nec one nine nine one zx one one needs a name agree with any of this anyway i was raised by a pack of wild corn dogs